Use ASP.NET Core's **`WebApplicationFactory<T>`** — it hosts your app in-process with an in-memory test server, so you get real HTTP round-trips with zero network overhead.

### Setup

```bash
dotnet add tests/MyMcp.Tests package Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc.Testing
dotnet add tests/MyMcp.Tests package xunit
```

### Example test

```csharp
public class McpIntegrationTests : IClassFixture<WebApplicationFactory<Program>>
{
    private readonly HttpClient _client;

    public McpIntegrationTests(WebApplicationFactory<Program> factory)
    {
        _client = factory.CreateClient();
    }

    [Fact]
    public async Task Initialize_ReturnsServerCapabilities()
    {
        var request = new
        {
            jsonrpc = "2.0",
            id = 1,
            method = "initialize",
            @params = new
            {
                protocolVersion = "2025-03-26",
                capabilities = new { },
                clientInfo = new { name = "test-client", version = "1.0" }
            }
        };

        var response = await _client.PostAsJsonAsync("/mcp", request);

        response.EnsureSuccessStatusCode();
        var body = await response.Content.ReadFromJsonAsync<JsonElement>();
        Assert.Equal("2.0", body.GetProperty("jsonrpc").GetString());
        Assert.Equal(1, body.GetProperty("id").GetInt32());
        Assert.True(body.GetProperty("result").TryGetProperty("capabilities", out _));
    }

    [Fact]
    public async Task ToolsList_ReturnsRegisteredTools()
    {
        var request = new { jsonrpc = "2.0", id = 2, method = "tools/list" };

        var response = await _client.PostAsJsonAsync("/mcp", request);

        response.EnsureSuccessStatusCode();
        var body = await response.Content.ReadFromJsonAsync<JsonElement>();
        var tools = body.GetProperty("result").GetProperty("tools");
        Assert.True(tools.GetArrayLength() > 0);
    }
}
```

### Key points

- **`WebApplicationFactory<Program>`** boots your real `Program.cs` pipeline (middleware, DI, routing) behind an in-memory `TestServer` — no port, no process.
- Swap dependencies (e.g., databases) by overriding `ConfigureWebHost` on the factory.
- For **SSE** endpoints, use `factory.CreateDefaultClient()` and read the response stream with `ReadAsStreamAsync()`.
- For **Streamable HTTP** (`Content-Type: text/event-stream` responses), set `HttpCompletionOption.ResponseHeadersRead` so you can consume the SSE stream incrementally.
- Make sure `Program.cs` exposes a partial class or uses top-level statements so the factory can discover the entry point. Add this to your server project if needed:

```csharp
// At bottom of Program.cs
public partial class Program { }
```

This gives you full protocol-level coverage (JSON-RPC framing, headers, status codes) without any real network I/O.
